{{Infobox aircraft occurrence |name = 1961 President Airlines Douglas DC-6 crash |occurrence_type = Accident |image = Douglas DC-6 I-DIMB SAM.jpg |image_size = 350 |alt = |caption = A Douglas DC-6 similar to the accident aircraft. |date = {{Start date|1961|09|10}} |summary = Possible pilot error due to instrument failure and bad weather, causing a loss of control |site = [[River Shannon]], Ireland |coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|type:event|display=inline,title}} --> <!--These 17 entries for single-aircraft occurrence:------> |aircraft_type = [[Douglas DC-6B]] |aircraft_name = ''Theodore Roosevelt'' |operator = President Airlines |tail_number = N90773 |origin = [[Düsseldorf Airport]], [[Düsseldorf]], Germany |stopover = [[Shannon Airport]], [[Shannon, County Clare]], Ireland |stopover0 = |stopover1 = |stopover2 = |stopover3 = |last_stopover = [[Gander International Airport]], [[Gander, Newfoundland]] |destination = [[Chicago O'Hare International Airport]], [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], United States |passengers = 77 |crew = 6 |injuries = |fatalities = 83 |survivors = 0 }}
The '''1961 President Airlines Douglas DC-6 crash''' occurred on the night of September 10, 1961, when a President Airlines [[Douglas DC-6|Douglas DC-6B]] named ''Theodore Roosevelt'' <ref name="Airmail book">{{Cite book |last=Vogt |first=Ronny |title=Irish Crash Airmails |publisher=Irish Airmail Society |year=1997 |location=Bray |pages=281 |isbn= }}</ref> outbound from [[Shannon, County Clare|Shannon]], Ireland crashed into the nearby [[River Shannon]] shortly after takeoff, killing all 83 people on board. To date, the crash remains the deadliest one in Irish territory, as well as the third-deadliest involving a DC-6 after [[LAN Chile Flight 107]] and [[Olympic Airways Flight 954]].<ref name="ASN">{{cite news|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19610910-0|title=Aviation Safety Network|date=}}</ref>
==Aircraft and occupants==
The aircraft involved in the accident was a Douglas DC-6B registered N90773. It first flew in 1953 and was powered by four Pratt & Whitney R-2800 engines. The aircraft's occupants on the accident flight consisted of 77 passengers and six crew members.<ref name="ASN"/>
==Accident== The aircraft was on a non-scheduled international passenger flight from [[Düsseldorf]], Germany to [[Chicago]] with stopovers in Shannon and [[Gander, Newfoundland and Labrador|Gander]], [[Newfoundland]] for refueling. Shortly after takeoff from Shannon Airport's runway 24, the pilots were cleared for a right-hand turn, but they instead turned left and kept turning until the aircraft had reached a bank angle of about 90 degrees or more. Unable to recover, the aircraft plummeted into the River Shannon 5,000&nbsp;ft. from the end of the runway. There were no survivors among the 83 passengers and crew. Subsequent investigations indicate that the crash probably resulted from a malfunctioning [[attitude indicator]], a fault in the starboard [[aileron]]s, or both. Poor weather conditions and crew fatigue were also cited as possible contributing factors.<ref name="ASN"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.planecrashinfo.com/1961/1961-35.htm|title=Plane Crash Info|date=}}</ref> Irish State Papers released in 1994 indicated that the pilot had alcohol in his blood and that the airline was insolvent at the time of the accident.<ref name="Airmail book"/>
==See also== *[[Air India Flight 855]] – another accident in which the attitude indicator failed, causing the pilot to bank too far to the left and lose control. *[[Aero Flight 311]] – another aircraft in which crew had alcohol before flight; it also banked to the left before crashing.
