The '''Cowardin classification system''' is a system for [[Wetland classification|classifying wetlands]], devised by Lewis M. Cowardin ''et al.'' in 1979 for the [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service]]. The system includes five main types of [[wetland]]<nowiki/>s: # Marine wetlands- which are areas exposed to the open [[ocean]] # Estuarine wetlands- partially enclosed by land and also exposed to a mixture of fresh and salt water bodies of water # [[Riverine]] wetlands- associated with flowing water # [[Lacustrine]] wetlands- associated with a [[lake]] or other body of fresh water # [[Palustrine]] wetlands- freshwater wetlands not associated with a river or lake. The primary purpose of this ecological classification system was to establish consistent terms and definitions used in inventory of wetlands and to provide standard measurements for mapping these lands.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cowardin|first=Lewis M.|last2=Golet|first2=Francis C.|date=1995-06-01|title=US Fish and Wildlife Service 1979 wetland classification: A review|journal=Vegetatio|language=en|volume=118|issue=1–2|pages=139–152|doi=10.1007/BF00045196|issn=0042-3106}}</ref>
==See also== * [[Wetland conservation]] * [[Wetlands of the United States]]
