{{refimprove|date=March 2018}}'''Energy in [[Benin]]''' is derived from multiple sources, including, oil and natural gas.

==Oil==
Production from the Sémé off shore oil field began in October 1982, operated by [[Saga Petroleum]], a [[Norway|Norwegian]] company working under a service contract. The field yielded {{convert|1.35|Moilbbl|m3}} of oil in 1991. In 1990, [[Benin]] exported an estimated {{convert|1.27|Moilbbl|m3}} of [[crude oil]]. In 1986, the contract was transferred to Pan Ocean Oil (Panoco), a [[Switzerland|Swiss]]-based US company, but loans to Benin from international development agencies were frozen because the company could not furnish satisfactory financial and capability statements; it withdrew, forcing Benin to take over production. [[Oil reserves|Reserves]], estimated at {{convert|44|Moilbbl|m3}}, were considered sufficient to meet domestic needs. However, Benin has no [[Oil refinery|refinery]]; consequently, refined [[petroleum]] products have to be re-imported. In 2002, imports of refined petroleum products amounted to {{convert|12600|oilbbl/d|m3/d}}. The company responsible for petroleum imports is [[Société Nationale de Commercialisation des Produits Pétroliers]] (SONACOP).

Benin ceased [[petroleum]] production from its Seme oilfield in 1998. America's [[Kosmos Energy|Kosmos Energy LLC]] explored for petroleum in 2006.<ref name=usgs>Omayra Bermúdez-Lugo. [http://minerals.usgs.gov/minerals/pubs/country/2006/myb3-2006-bn-uv-tp.pdf "The Mineral Industry of Benin, Burkina Faso, and Sao Tome e Principe"]. ''2006 [[Minerals Yearbook]]''. [[U.S. Geological Survey]] (October 2007). ''This article incorporates text from this U.S. government source, which is in the [[public domain]].</ref>

==Natural gas==
Although Benin has natural gas reserves, natural gas production is not active. The company responsible for gas imports is [[Société Beninoise de Gaz]]. Natural gas is supplied to Benin by the [[West African Gas Pipeline]].

==Electricity==

[[Electricity generation|Electrical generating]] capacity in 2002, totaled 122&nbsp;MW. Total domestic power output in that same year was 55&nbsp;GWh, of which [[Hydroelectricity|hydropower]] accounted for 2&nbsp;GWh and fossil fuels for the rest. Electricity consumption in 2002 was 488&nbsp;GWh. An agreement was signed with [[Togo]] and [[Ghana]] in 1967 under which Benin receives low-cost electric power from [[Akosombo Dam]] on the [[Volta River]] in Ghana. Total electricity imports for 2002 were estimated at 437&nbsp;GWh. Togo and Benin are constructing a dam on the [[Mono River]], along the Togo border, that will feed a [[power station]] to supply the southern regions of both countries. Benin also imports electricity from Nigeria through the [[CEB-NEPA Power Interconnection]], commissioned in 2007.

