The '''Icelandic Forest Service''' ({{lang-is|Skógræktin}}) is a subordinate [[government agency|agency]] to the Ministry for the Environment and Natural Resources of the [[Government of Iceland]]. The Icelandic Forest Research Mógilsá ({{lang-is|Rannsóknastöð skógræktar}}) is a research division of the Icelandic Forest Service with headquarters located at {{ill|Mógilsá|is}}, near [[Reykjavík]]. Their head of research is [[Edda Sigurdís Oddsdóttir]].

Iceland has been almost entirely devoid of trees, the trees having been cut down since viking times, when Iceland had 40% forest cover.<ref>{{cite web |title=Iceland is replanting its forests 1,000 years after vikings razed them |url=https://inhabitat.com/iceland-is-regrowing-its-forests-1000-years-after-vikings-razed-them/ |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> The forest service has a programme to encourage people to grow trees on Iceland,<ref>{{cite web |title=Vikings Razed the Forests. Can Iceland Regrow Them? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/10/20/climate/iceland-trees-reforestation.html |accessdate=28 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref> planting millions of seeds each year.<ref>{{cite web |title=After 1,000 Years, Iceland Is Growing Forests Again {{!}} Science Trends |url=https://sciencetrends.com/1000-years-iceland-growing-forests/ |website=Science Trends |accessdate=28 June 2018 |date=12 January 2018}}</ref> Iceland currently has about 2% forest cover.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Foundation |first1=Thomson Reuters |title=Spades, saplings and sheep: Iceland battles to restore long-lost forests |url=http://news.trust.org/item/20171225200102-53e7c/ |website=news.trust.org |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref>

The forest service has historically promoted Alaskan Lupines as an aid to reforestation, initially introduced in 1885, and widely spread from 1960 onwards to combat soil erosion.<ref>{{cite web |title=ALASKAN “WOLF” INVADES ICELAND - The Reykjavik Grapevine |url=https://grapevine.is/mag/articles/2011/08/25/alaskan-wolf-invades-iceland/ |website=The Reykjavik Grapevine |accessdate=28 June 2018 |date=25 August 2011}}</ref> But the plants have turned out to be invasive and spread everywhere, overunning native plants.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Magazine |first1=Hakai |title=Why Iceland Is Turning Purple {{!}} Hakai Magazine |url=https://www.hakaimagazine.com/features/why-iceland-is-turning-purple/ |website=Hakai Magazine |accessdate=28 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Whether introducing the plant was a good idea is contentious.<ref>{{cite web |title=Iceland’s Purple Fields |url=https://www.sciencewanders.com/icelands-purple-fields/ |website=www.sciencewanders.com |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref>

