'''Nathaniel Pryor Reed''' (July 22, 1933 – July 11, 2018) was an American environmentalist and political aide from [[Florida]] who served as an environmental adviser to Florida Governor [[Claude R. Kirk Jr.]] in the 1960s. He was also Assistant Secretary of Fish, Wildlife and Parks at the [[United States Department of the Interior]] from 1971 to 1977 serving under Presidents [[Richard Nixon]] and [[Gerald Ford]], where he co-wrote the [[Endangered Species Act of 1973]].<ref name="Miami Herald obit">{{cite news |last1=Harris |first1=Alex |title=Nathaniel Reed, icon of Everglades protection, dies at 84. He co-wrote the Endangered Species Act |url=https://miamiherald.com/news/local/environment/article214710885.html |work=Miami Herald |date=July 11, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref name="NYT obit">{{cite news |last1=Sandomir |first1=Richard |title=Nathaniel Reed, 84, Champion of Florida’s Environment, Is Dead |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/13/obituaries/nathaniel-reed-84-champion-of-floridas-environment-is-dead.html |work=The New York Times |date=July 13, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Reed was born in [[Manhattan]], New York City, and attended [[Deerfield Academy]] in Massachusetts and [[Trinity College (Connecticut)|Trinity College]], Connecticut. He served four years in the U.S. Air Force before becoming vice president of his family's real estate business.<ref name="NYT obit" /><ref>{{cite book |last1=Axelrod |first1=Alan |last2=Phillips |first2=Charles |title=The Environmentalists: A Biographical Dictionary from the 17th Century to the Present |date=1993 |publisher=Facts on File |location=New York |isbn=9780816027156|page=193}}</ref>
