The '''Somerset Wind Farm''' is a [[wind farm]] in [[Somerset County, Pennsylvania]] with six [[GE 1.5 MW wind turbine|GE 1.5 MW Wind Turbine]]s that began commercial operation in October 2001. The [[wind farm]] has a combined total [[Intermittent power source#Terminology|nameplate capacity]] of 9 MW, and produces about 25,000 megawatt-hours of electricity annually, which is roughly a 30% [[capacity factor]].<ref>[http://www.exeloncorp.com/ourcompanies/powergen/fossil/renewables/somerset_wind_farm.htm Exelon | Somerset Wind Farm<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070405141130/http://www.exeloncorp.com/ourcompanies/powergen/fossil/renewables/somerset_wind_farm.htm |date=2007-04-05 }}</ref> The wind farm was constructed by [[NextEra Energy Resources]], based in [[Florida]].<ref>[http://www.pawindenergynow.org/pa/farms.html Wind Farms in Pennsylvania] Pennsylvania Wind Working Group, accessed March 1, 2010.</ref>
The wind farm is just one-half mile ({{convert|.5|mi|disp=output only}}) south of the [[Pennsylvania Turnpike]], which makes its {{convert|215|ft|m|adj=mid|-tall}}<ref>[http://www.upenn.edu/pennnews/article.php?id=453 Penn Announces Largest U.S. Wind-Energy Purchase] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091129100548/http://www.upenn.edu/pennnews/article.php?id=453 |date=2009-11-29 }}</ref> towers easily visible to turnpike travelers.<ref>[http://www.horizonwind.com/projects/whatwevedone/somerset.aspx Welcome to Horizon Wind Energy<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070218035507/http://www.horizonwind.com/projects/whatwevedone/somerset.aspx |date=2007-02-18 }}</ref>
